<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,310,406,432]" box="[189,310,406,432]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,406,432]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,406,432]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,1399,455,630]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
This species is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Almeida &amp; Christenhusz &amp; Wanderley &amp; Cordeiro &amp; Melo &amp; Batista &amp; Felix, 2021" authorityName="Almeida &amp; Christenhusz &amp; Wanderley &amp; Cordeiro &amp; Melo &amp; Batista &amp; Felix" authorityYear="2021" box="[703,819,455,481]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Ameroglossum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alatum" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[703,819,455,481]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">A. alatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[826,919,455,481]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in having lustrous branches and leaves, winged pedicels, and white trichomes on the lower lip of the corolla tube. It differs in having green or slightly purplish vegetative portions (vs completely green), wings not evident (vs strongly winged), inflorescence usually a compound dichasium (vs simple dichasium) and the dorsal sepal partially covering the lateral sepals (vs the sepals not overlapping).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,324,670,696]" box="[189,324,670,696]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,670,696]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,670,696]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,1401,718,855]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
The specific epithet is the Latin adjective ʻ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. M. Almeida, A. M. Wanderley &amp; L. P. Felix" authorityYear="2021" box="[693,778,718,744]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Ameroglossum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[693,778,718,744]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ʼ, ʻtwo-coloredʼ, referring to the vegetative variation observed in its populations. Among the four populations described here, it was possible to encounter green or purplish, almost wine-coloured, plants in the same population, a characteristic only observed in this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
